Sierra Leone's electoral commission said Julius Maada Bio, leader of the opposition People's Party, was about 15,000 votes ahead of rival Samura Kamara, with 75 percent of the ballots counted. According to partial results, Bio had 43.4 percent of the vote, while Kamara of the ruling All People's Congress (APC) had 42.6 percent. The other two main candidates — Kandeh Yumkella and Samuel Sam-Sumana — were on 7 percent and 3.4 percent, respectively. Read more: Sierra Leone: Voting for change or more of the same? Full results are expected in the next few days. If no candidate garners the 55 percent needed to win the first round, the vote will go to a runoff. Read more: Sierra Leone heads into hotly contested elections Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
